.TH "IFCFG\-IPVLAN" "5" "November 2024" "Wicked User Manual" ""
.SH NAME
ifcfg\-ipvlan \- IPVLAN interface configuration
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]/etc/sysconfig/network/ifcfg\-*\f[R]
.SH IPVLAN interface
To set up an IPVLAN interface, you need a configuration file with the
\f[CR]IPVLAN=yes\f[R] variable set.
.PP
An IPVLAN interface is conceptually similar to MACVLAN, see the
following comparison:
.IP \[bu] 2
MACVLAN operates at Layer 2 and assigns unique MAC address to each
MACVLAN.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
Management support on most (L3+) managed switches
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.IP \[bu] 2
Common DHCP support
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
IPVLAN operates at Layer 3 and shares the MAC address with the
underlying interface.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.RS 2
.IP \[bu] 2
Supposed to be used with Advanced Router Configuration when the switches
restrict the maximum number of mac addresses (or ACLs) per physical
port.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.IP \[bu] 2
Limited SLAAC and DHCPv6 support
.RE
.PP
For detailed information, refer to the kernel documentation:
https://docs.kernel.org/networking/ipvlan.html
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[CR]IPVLAN <yes|no>\f[R]
This option must be set to \f[B]yes\f[R] to identify this configuration
type as IPVLAN.
.TP
\f[CR]IPVLAN_DEVICE\f[R]
Mandatory option to specify the lower (parent) interface for this IPVLAN
interface.
.TP
\f[CR]IPVLAN_MODE <l2|l3|l3s>\f[R]
Specifies the operational mode for the IPVLAN interface.
For a given lower device, you can select one of these modes and all
linked devices will operate in the same mode.
.RS
.PP
Default: \f[B]l3\f[R]
.RE
.TP
\f[CR]IPVLAN_FLAGS <bridge|private|vepa>\f[R]
Specifies the mode flags.
Only one flag at a time is allowed.
Similar to \f[CR]IPVLAN_MODE\f[R] a given flag will be applied to all
linked devices of one lower interface.
.RS
.PP
Default: \f[B]bridge\f[R]
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
Example \f[CR]ifcfg\-<name>\f[R] config file for an IPVLAN interface
.IP
.EX
STARTMODE=auto
BOOTPROTO=static
IPADDR=10.0.0.100/24

IPVLAN=yes
IPVLAN_DEVICE=eth0
IPVLAN_MODE=l3s
IPVLAN_FLAGS=bridge
.EE
